'''Hydrosal Gel''' is a [[brand name]] for a first-line topical gel treatment for [[excessive sweating]]. The product is a registered trademark of Valeo Pharma Inc. Hydrosal Gel contains 15% [[Aluminum chloride|aluminum chloride hexahydrate]], an ingredient often used in strong [[antiperspirants]], as well as a [[hydroalcoholic]] [[salicylic acid]] gel base.

Hydrosal Gel has a low risk of irritation due to its proprietary gel base. Clinical studies have demonstrated that the gel vehicle is better tolerated than an alcohol solution most commonly found in other products for excessive sweating, resulting in less irritation.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Newman|first=Jerry L.|author2=John C. Seitz|title=Intermittent use of an antimicrobial hand gel for reducing soap-induced irritation of health care personnel|journal=American Journal of Infection Control|date=June 1990|volume=18|issue=3|pages=194–200|url=http://www.ajicjournal.org/article/0196-6553(90)90184-T/abstract|accessdate=28 May 2013|pmid=2363539}}</ref> In addition to decreasing perspiration, Hydrosal Gel reduces odours.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Hölzle|first=Erhard|author2=Uwe Neubert|title=Antimicrobial effects of an antiperspirant formulation containing aqueous aluminum chloride hexahydrate|journal=Archives of Dermatological Research|date=1 September 1982|volume=272|issue=3–4|pages=321–329|doi=10.1007/BF00509063}}</ref> Clinical studies support the efficacy and low incidence of irritation of the 15% aluminum chloride and 2% salicylic acid gel base formula.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Woolery-Lloyd|first=Heather|author2=Whitney Valins|title=Aluminum chloride hexahydrate in a salicylic acid gel base: a case series of combination therapy with botulinum toxin type A for moderate to severe hyperhidrosis|journal=Cutaneous Medicine for the Practitioner|date=July 2011|volume=88|issue=1|pages=43–45|pmid=21877507}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Flanagan|first=Katherine H.|author2=Dee Anna Glaser|title=An open-label trial of the efficacy of 15% aluminum chloride in 2% salicylic acid gel base in the treatment of moderate-to-severe primary axillary hyperhidrosis.|journal=Journal of Drugs in Dermatology|date=May 2009|volume=8|issue=5|pages=477–480|pmid=19537371}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Benohanian|first=Antranik|author2=Alain Dansereau |author3=Chantal Bolduc |author4=Ernest Bloom |title=Localized hyperhidrosis treated with aluminum chloride in a salicylic acid gel base|journal=International Journal of Dermatology|date=September 1998|volume=37|issue=9|pages=701–703|doi=10.1046/j.1365-4362.1998.00543.x}}</ref>

