The '''Organization of Petroleum Importing Countries ''' was a cartel (or a proposal for a cartel)  of countries that primarily consume petroleum, to counter the influence of [[OPEC]], the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.<ref>Rosemary H. T. O'Kane "A Probabilistic Approach to the Causes of Coups d'Etat", ''British Journal of Political Science,'' Vol. 11, No. 3 (Jul., 1981), pp. 287-308 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/193491 Jstor]</ref><ref>"Energy and the Balance of Payments", by Charles F. Stewart ''Proceedings of the Academy of Political Science" Vol. 31, No. 2, The National Energy Problem (Dec., 1973), pp. 137-147  [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1173576 JSTOR]</ref>

It was reported in the early 1980s that [[Costa Rica]] had led the establishment of a group of countries under this name.<ref>Paul Hallwood and Stuart Sinclair, "OPEC'S Developing Relationships with the Third World" ''International Affairs'', Vol. 58, No. 2 (Spring, 1982), pp. 271-286 [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2617982 Jstor]</ref>

There were also calls in the early 21st century for an organization fulfilling such a role.<ref>''Fueling Asia’s growth: Collaboration in energy security '' by Deloitte's Global Energy & Resources Group and Deloitte’s China Practice  [www.deloitte.com/dtt/cda/doc/content/E&R-eng_sec.pdf Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu report], 2007</ref> It was argued that it was in the interests of [[developing countries]]<ref>http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=439680</ref><ref>http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=1306919</ref><ref>http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=1262716e</ref> and that it would also act to the benefit of [[developed countries]].<ref>Jayanta Sen,  "Buyers' Cartel for Oil? Feasible and a Free Lunch Worth $5 Trillion to $50 Trillion for the US!" [http://ssrn.com/abstract=869120 SSRN Working Papers Series]</ref>

