{{Redirect2|Sheqel|Shekalim|the currency of the State of Israel|Israeli new shekel}} {{For|the Talmudic tractate|Shekalim (Talmud)}} {{further|Ancient Mesopotamian units of measurement}} [[File:Carthage EL shekel 2250013.jpg|thumb|300px|An [[electrum]] [[Ancient Carthage|Carthaginian]] shekel, c. 310–290 BC, bearing the image of [[Tanit]], consort of [[Baʿal Hammon]].]] [[File:C+B-Shekel-FigC-TyrianHalfShekel.PNG|thumb|300px|A [[silver]] [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyrian]] half-shekel from 102&nbsp;{{sc|bc}} bearing the image of [[Melqart]], the Tyrian [[Hercules]].]] [[Image:Half Shekel.jpg|thumb|300px|A [[silver]] [[Jerusalem shekel]] ({{sc|ad}} 68) from the [[First Jewish-Roman War|First Jewish Revolt]] against [[Roman Empire|Roman rule]]. The [[obverse]] inscription reads "Shekel of Israel&nbsp;/ Year 3" and that on the [[obverse and reverse|reverse]] "[[Jerusalem]] the Holy".]] [[Image:Barkokhba-silver-tetradrachm.jpg|300px|thumb|A [[silver]] [[Bar Kochba shekel]] from [[Simon bar Kokhba]]'s [[Bar Kochba Revolt|revolt]] against [[Roman Empire|Roman rule]]. [[Obverse]]: The [[Temple in Jerusalem|Temple]] façade with a rising star surrounded by "Simon". [[Obverse and reverse|Reverse]]: A [[lulav]] surrounded by "To the Freedom of [[Jerusalem]]".]] [[File:Israel 1 Shekel 1978 Obverse & Reverse.jpg|thumb|300px|The [[Old Israeli Shekel|IS]]&nbsp;1 [[Old Israeli shekel#Notes|banknote]], issued in 1980 but then discontinued.]] [[File:1 old Shekel coin.jpg|300px|thumb|The [[cupronickel]] [[Israel]]i [[Israeli old shekel|shekel]] (properly "sheqel" and now known as the "old shekel"), issued between 1981 and 1985, when it was replaced owing to its [[hyperinflation]]. ]] [[File:Israel 1 Sheqel 1986 Obverse & Reverse.jpg|300px|thumb|The [[New Israeli Shekel|NIS]]&nbsp;1 [[Israeli banknotes|banknote]], issued in 1986 but since discontinued.]] [[File:Nis 1 sheqel.png|300px|thumb|The [[cupronickel]] [[Israel]]i [[Israeli new shekel|new shekel]] (properly "new sheqel"), the present currency of the state of [[Israel]].]] '''Shekel''' ([[Akkadian (language)|Akkadian]]: ''šiqlu'' or ''siqlu''; {{lang-he-n|שקל}}, {{abbr|pl|plural}}. '''shekels''' or '''sheqalim''') is any of several ancient units of weight or of currency. Since it was a coin that represented a claim on a weight of [[barley]] held in the city warehouse, the term "shekel" was likely used in both contexts: 1) As the name of the coin, and; 2) To describe the measure of barley. This coin weighed about 180 [[Grain (unit)|grains]] (11 [[gram]]s or .35 [[troy ounce]]s).
{{anchor|Etymology}}
==Name== The [[Hebrew]] word ''shekel'' is based on the [[Semitic languages|Semitic]] verbal root for "weighing" ({{sc|šql}}), cognate to the [[Akkadian (language)|Akkadian]] ''šiqlu'' or ''siqlu'', a unit of weight equivalent to the [[Sumerian language|Sumerian]] ''gin2''.<ref>{{cite book | title= Mathematics and measurement| first = Oswald Ashton Wentworth | last = Dilke|year= 1987 |publisher= University of California Press |page= 46|url= https://books.google.com./books?id=AKJZvXOS7n4C&pg=PA46 |accessdate= 6 February 2011}}</ref> Use of the word was first attested in c. 2150 BC during the [[Akkadian Empire]] under the reign of [[Naram-Sin of Akkad|Naram-Sin]], and later in c. 1700 BC in the [[Code of Hammurabi]]. The {{sc|šql}} root is found in the Hebrew words for "to weigh" (''shaqal''), "weight" (''mishqal'') and "consideration" (''shiqqul''), and is related to the {{sc|tql}} root in [[Aramaic]] and the {{sc|θql}} root in [[Arabic]], such as the words ''thiqal'' (the weight) or ''Mithqal'' (unit of weight). The famous [[The writing on the wall|writing on the wall]] in the Biblical [[Book of Daniel]] includes a cryptic use of the word in Aramaic: "Mene, mene, teqel, u-farsin". The word "shekel" came into the English language via the [[Hebrew Bible]], where it is first used in the [[Book of Genesis]].<ref>Genesis 23:15-16</ref>
==History== The earliest shekels were a unit of weight, used as other units such as grams and troy ounces for trading before the advent of coins. The shekel was common among western [[Semitic peoples]]. [[Moab]]ites, [[Edom]]ites, and [[Phoenicia]]ns used the shekel, although proper coinage developed very late. [[Carthaginian coinage]] was based on the shekel and may have preceded its home town of [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]] in issuing proper coins.<ref name="brony" />
Coins were used and may have been invented by the early [[Ancient Anatolians|Anatolian]] traders who stamped their marks to avoid weighing each time used. [[Herodotus]] states that the first coinage was issued by [[Croesus]], King of [[Lydia]], spreading to the golden [[Daric]] (worth 20 [[Achaemenid coinage|''sigloi'']] or shekel),<ref>{{Citation|title=Encyclopædia Britannica|contribution=Siglos|contribution-url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/543654/siglos}}.</ref> issued by the [[Persian Empire]] and the silver Athenian [[obolus|obol]] and [[drachma]]. Early coins were money stamped with an official seal to certify their weight. Silver ingots, some with markings were issued. Later authorities decided who designed coins.{{Sfn | DIA | 1964}}
As with many ancient units, the shekel had a variety of values depending on era, government and region; weights between 7<ref name="dubya" /> and 17&nbsp;grams and values of 11,<ref>Tenney, Merril ed., ''The Zondervan Pictorial Encyclopedia of the Bible'', vol. 5, "Weights and Measures," Grand Rapids, MI: Zondervan, 1976.</ref> 14, and 17&nbsp;grams are common. When used to pay laborers, recorded wages in the ancient world range widely. The Code of Hammurabi (circa 1800 BC) sets the value of unskilled labor at approximately ten shekels per year of work.<ref name="BotterweckRinggren2004">{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=dMidce6H4WYC&pg=PA132 |title= Theological Dictionary of the Old Testament |date=21 June 2004 |publisher= Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing |isbn=978-0-8028-2345-8 |page=132 |author1= G. Johannes Botterweck |author2= Helmer Ringgren |author3= Heinz-Josef Fabry}}</ref> Later, records within the Persian Empire (539-333 BC) give ranges from a minimum of two shekels per month for unskilled labor, to as high as seven to ten shekels per month in some records.<ref name="Altmann20162">{{cite book |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=UrwJ76OkyY0C&pg=PA62 |title= Economics in Persian-Period Biblical Texts: Their Interactions with Economic Developments in the Persian Period and Earlier Biblical Traditions |date=26 October 2016 |publisher= Mohr Siebeck |isbn=978-3-16-154813-0 |page=62 |author= Peter Altmann}}</ref> A survival wage for an urban household during the Persian period would require at least 22 shekels of income per year.<ref name="Altmann20162" />
===Israelites=== {{Bibleref2|Exodus 30:24}} notes that the measures of the [[ingredients]] for the [[holy anointing oil]] were to be calculated using the '''Shekel of the Sanctuary''' (see also {{Bibleref2|Exodus 38:24–26}}, and similarly at {{Bibleref2|Numbers 3:47}} for payment for the redemption of 273 first-born males <ref>See [[Bemidbar (parsha)#Sixth reading — Numbers 3:40–51]]</ref> and at {{Bibleref2|Numbers 7:12–88}} for the offerings of the [[leaders of the tribes of Israel]]), suggesting that there were other common measures of shekel in use, or at least that the Temple authorities defined a standard for the shekel to be used for [[Temple of Solomon|Temple]] purposes.
According to Jewish law, whenever a census of the Jewish people was to be conducted, every person that was counted was required to pay the ''half-Shekel'' for his atonement ({{Bibleref2|Exodus 30:11–16}}).<ref>cf. [[Josephus]], ''[[Antiquities of the Jews|Antiquities]]'' (vii. 13, § 1)[http://sacred-texts.com/jud/josephus/ant-7.htm]</ref>
The Aramaic ''tekel'', similar to the Hebrew ''shekel'', used in [[the writing on the wall]] during the [[Belshazzar|feast of Belshazzar]] according to the [[Book of Daniel]] and defined as weighed, shares a common root with the word shekel and may even additionally attest to its original usage as a weight.
===Second Temple period half-Shekel Temple tax===<!--This section is linked from [[Moed]] and [[Adar]] and [[Hurvat Itri]] ([[MOS:HEAD]])--> [[File:JUDAEA_Half_Sheke.jpg|thumb|left|The half-Shekel coin discovered in [[Hurvat Itri|Horvat 'Ethry]]]] During the [[Second Temple]] period, it was customary among Jews to annually offer the ''half-Shekel'' into the Temple treasury, for the upkeep and maintenance of the Temple precincts, as also used in purchasing public animal-offerings. This practice not only applied to Jews living in the [[Land of Israel]], but also to Jews living outside the Land of Israel.<ref>[[Josephus]], ''[[Antiquities of the Jews|Antiquities]]'' (xviii. 9, § 1)</ref> Archaeological excavations conducted at [[Hurvat Itri|Horvat 'Ethry]] in Israel from 1999 to 2001 by [[Boaz Zissu]] and [[Amir Ganor]] of the [[Israeli Antiquities Authority]] (IAA) have yielded important finds, the most-prized of which being a ''half-Shekel'' coin minted in the 2nd century CE, upon which are embossed the words "Half-Shekel" in [[paleo-Hebrew]] ({{Lang-he-n|'''חצי השקל'''}}), and which same coin possesses a silver content of 6.87 grams.<ref>Boaz Zissu & Amir Ganor, ''Horvat Ethri — A Jewish Village from the Second Temple Period and the Bar Kokhba Revolt in the Judean Foothills'', Journal of Jewish Studies 60 (1), Oxford Centre for Hebrew and Jewish Studies, London 2009, pp. 96; 118.</ref> According to the Jewish historian [[Josephus]], the annual monetary tribute of the half-Shekel to the Temple at [[Jerusalem]] was equivalent to two [[Didrachm|Athenian drachmæ]], each Athenian or [[Attic]] drachma weighing a little over 4.3 grams.<ref>[[Josephus]], ''[[Wars of the Jews]]'' (vii. 6, § 6).</ref>
{{anchor|Carthaginian|Carthaginian shekel}}
===First and Second Jewish Revolt=== {{main |Jerusalem shekel|Bar Kochba shekel}} The '''[[Jerusalem]] [[Jerusalem shekel|shekel]]''' was issued from {{sc |ad}}&nbsp;66 to 70 amid the [[First Jewish-Roman War|First Jewish Revolt]] as a means of emphasizing the independence of [[Judaea]] from [[Roman Empire|Roman rule]].
The '''[[Bar Kochba]] [[Bar Kochba shekel|shekel]]''' was issued from {{sc |ad}}&nbsp;132 to 135 amid the [[Bar Kokhba Revolt]] for similar reasons.
===Carthage=== {{main|Carthaginian shekel}} The '''[[Ancient Carthage|Carthaginian]]''' or '''[[Punics|Punic]] [[Carthaginian shekel|shekel]]''' was typically around 7.2&nbsp;[[gram]]s in [[silver]] and 7.5&nbsp;[[gram]]s in [[gold]] (suggesting an exchange rate of 12:1).<ref name=dubya>{{citation |last=Crawford |first= Michael Hewson |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=84_G_8q6WQcC |title= Coinage and Money under the Roman Republic: Italy and the Mediterranean Economy |series=''The Library of Numismatics'' |editor= Philip Grierson |display-editors=0 |publisher= University of California Press |location= Berkeley |date=1985 |isbn=0-520-05506-3 }}</ref> They were apparently first developed on [[Carthaginian Sicily|Sicily]] during the mid-4th century {{sc|bc}}.<ref name=brony>{{ citation |last= Bronson |first= Bennet |title= Bulletin |volume=Vol. 47, No. 10 |date= November 1976 |publisher= Field Museum of Natural History |location= Chicago |url= https://archive.org/stream/fieldmuseumofnat47chica#page/n193/mode/2up |contribution= Cash, Cannon, and Cowrie Shells: The Nonmodern Moneys of the World |pp=3–15 }}.</ref> They were particularly associated with the payment of Carthage's mercenary armies and were repeatedly debased over the course of each of the [[Punic Wars]], although the [[Carthaginian Empire]]'s expansion into [[Carthaginian Spain|Spain]] under the [[Barcid dynasty|Barcids]] before the [[Second Punic War|Second]] and recovery under [[Hannibal]] before the [[Third Punic War|Third]] permitted improving the amount and quality of the currency. Throughout, it was more common for Carthage's holdings in [[North Africa]] to employ [[bronze]] or no coinage except when paying mercenary armies and for most of the [[coin|specie]] to circulate in [[Carthaginian Spain|Spain]], [[Carthaginian Sardinia|Sardinia]], and [[Carthaginian Sicily|Sicily]].<ref name=dubya/>
{{anchor|Tyrian|Tyrian shekel}}
===Tyre=== {{main|Tyrian shekel}} The '''[[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyrian]] [[Tyrian shekel|shekel]]''' began to be issued {{circa|lk=no|300}}&nbsp;{{sc|bc}}.<ref name=brony/> Owing to the relative purity of their silver, they were the preferred medium of payment for the [[Temple of Solomon|Temple]] tax in [[Jerusalem]] despite their royal and pagan imagery. The money changers assaulted by [[Jesus]] in the [[New Testament]] are those who exchanged worshippers' baser common currency for such shekels and they have been suggested as a possible coin used as the "[[Thirty pieces of silver|30 pieces of silver]]" in the [[New Testament]].<ref>{{Citation | author-link = Donald Wiseman| first = Donald J | last = Wiseman | title = Illustrations from Biblical Archaeology | place = London | publisher = Tyndale Press | year = 1958 | pages = 87–89}}.</ref>
{{anchor |Jerusalem shekel|Jerusalem|Bar Kochba|Bar Kochba Revolt|First Jewish Revolt|Bar Kochba shekel}}
==Present==
===Israel=== {{main|Old Shekel|New Shekel}} The '''[[Israel]]i [[old Israeli shekel|shekel]]''' (properly '''sheqel''') replaced the [[Israeli lira|Israeli lira or pound]] in 1980. Its [[currency sign]] was {{angle brackets|[[Image:Old Sheqel sign.svg|14px]]}}, although it was more commonly denominated as '''S''' or '''IS'''. It was subdivided into 100 [[new agora|new agoras or agorot]]. It suffered from [[hyperinflation]] and was quickly replaced.
The '''[[Israeli new shekel|new shekel]]''' replaced it in 1985. Its [[currency sign]] is {{nowrap|{{angle brackets|&thinsp;<big>[[₪]]</big>&thinsp;}},}} although it is often denominated as '''S''' or '''NS'''. It is subdivided into 100 [[Israeli agora|agoras or agorot]]. Both Israeli shekels are purely units of currency and not weight. With the 2014 series of notes, the [[Bank of Israel]] abandoned the [[romanization of Hebrew|transcription]]s ''Sheqel'' and ''Sheqalim'' in favor of the standard English forms ''Shekel'' and ''Shekels''.
